title: Site Preparation
prefix: site-prep
---
[root] Site Preparation (notstarted)
Prepare the land and utilities before construction begins.
-> land
-> utilities-rough
---
[land] Land & Foundation Prep (notstarted)
Clear the site, level the ground, and prepare the foundation.
-> survey
-> clearing
-> foundation
---
[survey] Land Survey (notstarted)
Hire a licensed surveyor to mark property boundaries, setback lines, and easements.
Confirm the build footprint complies with all setback requirements.
---
[clearing] Site Clearing & Grading (notstarted)
Remove vegetation, stumps, and debris; grade the site for proper drainage.
Establish a level building pad with appropriate slope away from the foundation.
-> survey
---
[foundation] Foundation Installation (notstarted)
Install the chosen foundation system per engineered plans.
-> clearing
> Decision needed: trailer-based (mobile) vs. permanent foundation (piers/slab/skids).
> Trailer: flexibility to relocate; Piers/slab: more stable, may increase property value.
---
[utilities-rough] Utility Rough-In (notstarted)
Arrange water, sewer/septic, and electrical service to the site.
-> land
-> utility-trench
-> water-hookup
-> sewer-septic
-> electrical-service
---
[utility-trench] Utility Trench & Conduit (notstarted)
Dig trenches to required depth and lay conduit for underground utility runs.
Call 811 before digging to mark existing underground utilities.
-> clearing
---
[water-hookup] Water Supply Connection (notstarted)
Tap into municipal water or drill a well; run supply line to the build site.
Install a shut-off valve and pressure regulator at the connection point.
-> utility-trench
---
[sewer-septic] Sewer / Septic Connection (notstarted)
Connect to municipal sewer or install an approved septic system.
-> utility-trench
> Check local health department requirements for septic tank sizing and drain field.
> Composting toilet is an alternative if septic is prohibitively expensive.
---
[electrical-service] Electrical Service Drop (notstarted)
Coordinate with the utility company for a temporary construction panel or permanent service drop.
Determine amperage requirements (100A typical for a tiny home).
-> utility-trench
